                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d877">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2297: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-09-27T20:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 27, 1940—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 27—9:26 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>907. My 905, September 27, 6 p.m.<note n="53" xml:id="d877fn53">Not
                        printed.</note> The Vice Minister has just called me on the telephone and
                    said that the Foreign Minister had read my letter and authorized me to inform my
                    Government that there is no truth in the report that Japanese armed forces
                    propose forcibly to occupy the French Concession in Shanghai within the
                    immediate future. Mr. Ohashi said “there is nothing in it.”</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
